<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,385,1384]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,493,519]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Description.</emphasis>
Based on the 
<typeStatus box="[514,616,494,520]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">holotype</typeStatus>
: complete with up to 300 segments. TL= 
<quantity box="[1104,1187,494,520]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.8" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="mm" value="38.0">38 mm</quantity>
, TW= 2.3 mm. Body stiffed, long, narrowed posteriorly(
<figureCitation box="[542,642,530,556]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1410,181,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-26@38.[173,1413,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 18. Bhawatsonia nenoae n. sp., holotype (ECOSUR-269). A) Complete body. B) Parapodium from segment 142. C) Lateral palea. D) Subunit 1. E) Main palea. F–G) Median paleae. H) Unit 1. I) Unit 2. J–L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. N) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. Scales: 20 µm (CDHIJKLM), 50 µm (EFGN), 200 µm (B), 1 mm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702074" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702074/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18A</figureCitation>
). Body pale violet to brown, dorsal and ventral cirri bases darker. Paleae fan bright maroon to golden, non-imbricated dorsally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,385,1384]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Prostomium completely retracted among the first six, caused by the fixation method. Antennae, prostomium, nuchal organ not seen; eyes barely noticed. Palps long, cylindrical, visible only in ventral view. Mouth fold small, placed between segment 3 and 4. Pharynx eversible, not exposed and not detected by transparency.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,385,1384]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
Parapodium from segment 142, notochaetae in three main groups (
<figureCitation box="[967,1071,710,736]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1410,181,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-26@38.[173,1413,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 18. Bhawatsonia nenoae n. sp., holotype (ECOSUR-269). A) Complete body. B) Parapodium from segment 142. C) Lateral palea. D) Subunit 1. E) Main palea. F–G) Median paleae. H) Unit 1. I) Unit 2. J–L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. N) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. Scales: 20 µm (CDHIJKLM), 50 µm (EFGN), 200 µm (B), 1 mm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702074" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702074/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18B</figureCitation>
). Notochaetae: lateral group inserted below notaciculum, 2 paleae, very slender and symmetrical, with 2 internal ribs (
<figureCitation box="[1115,1216,746,772]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1410,181,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-26@38.[173,1413,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 18. Bhawatsonia nenoae n. sp., holotype (ECOSUR-269). A) Complete body. B) Parapodium from segment 142. C) Lateral palea. D) Subunit 1. E) Main palea. F–G) Median paleae. H) Unit 1. I) Unit 2. J–L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. N) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. Scales: 20 µm (CDHIJKLM), 50 µm (EFGN), 200 µm (B), 1 mm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702074" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702074/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18C</figureCitation>
); subunit 1, 1 palea, broader and symmetrical, with 12–14 internal ribs (
<figureCitation box="[723,827,782,808]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1410,181,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-26@38.[173,1413,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 18. Bhawatsonia nenoae n. sp., holotype (ECOSUR-269). A) Complete body. B) Parapodium from segment 142. C) Lateral palea. D) Subunit 1. E) Main palea. F–G) Median paleae. H) Unit 1. I) Unit 2. J–L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. N) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. Scales: 20 µm (CDHIJKLM), 50 µm (EFGN), 200 µm (B), 1 mm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702074" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702074/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18D</figureCitation>
). Main group, 14–16 paleae, broader and symmetrical, with 18–20 internal ribs (
<figureCitation box="[430,530,818,844]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1410,181,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-26@38.[173,1413,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 18. Bhawatsonia nenoae n. sp., holotype (ECOSUR-269). A) Complete body. B) Parapodium from segment 142. C) Lateral palea. D) Subunit 1. E) Main palea. F–G) Median paleae. H) Unit 1. I) Unit 2. J–L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. N) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. Scales: 20 µm (CDHIJKLM), 50 µm (EFGN), 200 µm (B), 1 mm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702074" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702074/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18E</figureCitation>
). Median group, 2 paleae, curved, shorter and asymmetrical; the distal-most palea with 13 internal ribs and, the proximal-most and smallest with 13 internal ribs (
<figureCitation box="[1040,1175,854,880]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1410,181,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-26@38.[173,1413,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 18. Bhawatsonia nenoae n. sp., holotype (ECOSUR-269). A) Complete body. B) Parapodium from segment 142. C) Lateral palea. D) Subunit 1. E) Main palea. F–G) Median paleae. H) Unit 1. I) Unit 2. J–L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. N) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. Scales: 20 µm (CDHIJKLM), 50 µm (EFGN), 200 µm (B), 1 mm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702074" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702074/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18F–G</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,385,1384]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
Neuropodium conical, smaller than the notopodium. Neurochaetae: unit 1, 2 superior spinigers, blades straight and long, 12–13 times longer than wide (
<figureCitation box="[614,719,926,952]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1410,181,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-26@38.[173,1413,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 18. Bhawatsonia nenoae n. sp., holotype (ECOSUR-269). A) Complete body. B) Parapodium from segment 142. C) Lateral palea. D) Subunit 1. E) Main palea. F–G) Median paleae. H) Unit 1. I) Unit 2. J–L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. N) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. Scales: 20 µm (CDHIJKLM), 50 µm (EFGN), 200 µm (B), 1 mm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702074" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702074/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18H</figureCitation>
). Unit 2, 8 falcigers, blades straight and short, 2–3 times longer as wide (
<figureCitation box="[253,373,962,988]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1410,181,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-26@38.[173,1413,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 18. Bhawatsonia nenoae n. sp., holotype (ECOSUR-269). A) Complete body. B) Parapodium from segment 142. C) Lateral palea. D) Subunit 1. E) Main palea. F–G) Median paleae. H) Unit 1. I) Unit 2. J–L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. N) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. Scales: 20 µm (CDHIJKLM), 50 µm (EFGN), 200 µm (B), 1 mm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702074" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702074/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18I–J</figureCitation>
). Unit 3, 6 falcigers, blades straight and short, 2–3 times longer than wide (
<figureCitation box="[1229,1367,962,988]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1410,181,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-26@38.[173,1413,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 18. Bhawatsonia nenoae n. sp., holotype (ECOSUR-269). A) Complete body. B) Parapodium from segment 142. C) Lateral palea. D) Subunit 1. E) Main palea. F–G) Median paleae. H) Unit 1. I) Unit 2. J–L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. N) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. Scales: 20 µm (CDHIJKLM), 50 µm (EFGN), 200 µm (B), 1 mm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702074" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702074/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18K–L</figureCitation>
). Unit 4, 2 falcigers, blades straight and medium-sized, 4–5 times longer than wide (
<figureCitation box="[1025,1135,998,1024]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1410,181,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-26@38.[173,1413,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 18. Bhawatsonia nenoae n. sp., holotype (ECOSUR-269). A) Complete body. B) Parapodium from segment 142. C) Lateral palea. D) Subunit 1. E) Main palea. F–G) Median paleae. H) Unit 1. I) Unit 2. J–L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. N) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. Scales: 20 µm (CDHIJKLM), 50 µm (EFGN), 200 µm (B), 1 mm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702074" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702074/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18M</figureCitation>
). Blades bidentate, bended distally. Pygidium conical, with two anal cirri (
<figureCitation box="[678,783,1034,1060]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1410,181,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-26@38.[173,1413,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 18. Bhawatsonia nenoae n. sp., holotype (ECOSUR-269). A) Complete body. B) Parapodium from segment 142. C) Lateral palea. D) Subunit 1. E) Main palea. F–G) Median paleae. H) Unit 1. I) Unit 2. J–L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. N) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. Scales: 20 µm (CDHIJKLM), 50 µm (EFGN), 200 µm (B), 1 mm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702074" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702074/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18N</figureCitation>
). Oocytes not seen.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,385,1384]" box="[199,1110,1069,1096]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,1069,1095]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Habitat.</emphasis>
Subtidal. The specimen examined was collected as epibiont of bivalves.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,900,1105,1133]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,385,1384]" box="[199,900,1105,1133]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1105,1131]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Distribution.</emphasis>
Only known from Acapulco, 
<collectingRegion box="[687,788,1106,1132]" country="Mexico" name="Guerrero" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Guerrero</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation box="[803,888,1106,1133]" captionStart="FIGURE 26" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1898,1922]" captionTargetBox="[172,1414,917,1868]" captionTargetId="figure-379@49.[166,1422,913,1874]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 26. Previous and new records of chrysopetalids in the Tropical Eastern Pacific. Empty symbols indicate historic records." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702090" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702090/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,385,1384]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1142,1168]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Cruz-Gómez, 2021" authorityName="Cruz-Gómez" authorityYear="2021" box="[323,436,1143,1168]" class="Polychaeta" family="Chrysopetalidae" genus="Bhawatsonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="nenoae" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[323,436,1143,1168]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">B. nenoae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[444,507,1142,1168]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[444,507,1142,1168]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cruz-Gómez" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Rioja" baseAuthorityYear="1947" box="[635,770,1143,1168]" class="Polychaeta" family="Chrysopetalidae" genus="Bhawatsonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="purpurea" status="n. comb.">
<emphasis box="[635,770,1143,1168]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">B. purpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[778,881,1142,1168]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[778,881,1142,1168]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" rank="species">n. comb.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
in having slender main paleae and broad median paleae, but they can be differentiated using the form of main paleae and the features present in the subunit 1 paleae (see 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cruz-Gómez" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Rioja" baseAuthorityYear="1947" box="[203,337,1215,1240]" class="Polychaeta" family="Chrysopetalidae" genus="Bhawatsonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="purpurea" status="n. comb.">
<emphasis box="[203,337,1215,1240]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">B. purpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[343,445,1214,1240]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[343,445,1214,1240]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" rank="species">n. comb.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
remarks). Moreover, specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="Cruz-Gómez, 2021" authorityName="Cruz-Gómez" authorityYear="2021" box="[841,953,1215,1240]" class="Polychaeta" family="Chrysopetalidae" genus="Bhawatsonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="nenoae" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[841,953,1215,1240]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">B. nenoae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[959,1021,1214,1240]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[959,1021,1214,1240]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be easily recognized by possessing the proximal-most median palea drop-like shape.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,385,1384]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1286,1312]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is named after the author’s sister, Jaemy Cruz-Gómez, aka “Neno”, in recognition of her support and company during our childhood and even now regardless of the distance. The epithet is a noun in the genitive case (
<bibRefCitation author="ICZN" box="[311,444,1358,1384]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" refId="ref37026" refString="ICZN (1999) International Code of Zoological Nomenclature. 4 th Edition. International Trust for Zoological Nomenclature (The Natural History Museum), London, 306 pp." type="book" year="1999">ICZN 1999</bibRefCitation>
, Art. 31.1.2).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
